# Wine, Cheese & Gastronomy — World Cheeses

# ── Cheese type categories ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:type:fresh" "Unaged cheese with high moisture, soft texture, mild and milky flavor. No rind development. Examples: ricotta, mozzarella, chèvre frais, cream cheese. Eaten within days of production."
def "cheese:type:soft_ripened" "Cheese with bloomy white rind from Penicillium camemberti mold. Soft, creamy interior. Ripens from outside in. Examples: Brie, Camembert, Chaource. Short aging (2-8 weeks)."
def "cheese:type:washed_rind" "Cheese whose rind is periodically washed with brine, wine, beer, or spirits. Orange-red sticky rind, pungent aroma, mild interior. Brevibacterium linens bacteria. Examples: Munster, Époisses, Taleggio."
def "cheese:type:semi_soft" "Cheese with pliable, supple interior and mild flavor. Moderate moisture. Often has natural or wax rind. Examples: Havarti, Fontina, Morbier, Edam. Versatile table and melting cheese."
def "cheese:type:hard" "Pressed cheese with low moisture, firm texture, and complex flavor developed over months. Examples: Cheddar, Manchego, Comté, Gouda (aged), Gruyère. Excellent for cooking and pairing."
def "cheese:type:extra_hard" "Very low moisture cheese aged 12+ months; granular, crystalline texture with intense umami. Grated or shaved. Examples: Parmigiano-Reggiano, Grana Padano, aged Pecorino, Sbrinz."
def "cheese:type:blue" "Cheese with blue-green mold (Penicillium roqueforti) introduced by needling to allow oxygen in. Sharp, pungent, creamy or crumbly. Examples: Roquefort, Gorgonzola, Stilton, Bleu d'Auvergne."
def "cheese:type:processed" "Cheese product made by melting natural cheese with emulsifying salts. Uniform texture, long shelf life, mild flavor. Examples: American cheese slices, Leerdammer-style, Laughing Cow."

# ── Milk type categories ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:milk:cow" "Cheese made from cow's milk. Most common milk type globally. Rich in fat, mild flavor base. Produces diverse styles from fresh to hard. Examples: Cheddar, Brie, Gruyère, Parmigiano."
def "cheese:milk:sheep" "Cheese made from sheep's milk (ewes' milk). Higher fat and protein than cow's milk; rich, lanolin, nutty flavor. Examples: Roquefort, Pecorino, Manchego, Ossau-Iraty, Feta (traditionally)."
def "cheese:milk:goat" "Cheese made from goat's milk (chèvre). Distinctive tang, chalky texture when fresh, earthy when aged. Examples: Crottin de Chavignol, Valençay, Selles-sur-Cher, Rocamadour."
def "cheese:milk:buffalo" "Cheese made from water buffalo milk. Richer than cow's milk, high in fat, pure white color. Examples: Mozzarella di Bufala Campana DOP. Buffalo also used in India for paneer variants."
def "cheese:milk:mixed" "Cheese made from blend of two or more milk types (cow+sheep, cow+goat, etc.). Examples: some Feta, Cabrales, Bryndza, certain Swiss alpine cheeses. Complexity from multiple milk flavors."

# ── France — PDO/AOC Cheeses ─────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:brie_de_meaux" "Soft-ripened AOC cow's milk cheese from Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France. 'King of cheeses.' Bloomy rind, supple ivory paste, mushroom and butter flavors. Minimum 4 weeks affinage."
def "cheese:brie_de_melun" "Soft-ripened AOC cow's milk cheese, smaller and stronger than Brie de Meaux. More assertive flavor, saltier, rustic rind. Longer affinage (minimum 4 weeks). Considered the 'original' Brie."
def "cheese:camembert_de_normandie" "Iconic AOC soft-ripened cow's milk cheese from Normandy. Bloomy rind, creamy interior, mushroom and barnyard notes. Made from raw milk in traditional wooden boxes. Minimum 21 days aging."
def "cheese:roquefort" "AOC blue cheese from Combalou caves, Aveyron. Sheep's milk. 'King of blue cheeses.' Blue-green Penicillium roqueforti veining, creamy, sharp, salty. Minimum 3 months cave aging."
def "cheese:comte" "AOC hard cow's milk cheese from Franche-Comté. Fruity, nutty, complex. 40+ flavor descriptors. Aged 4-24+ months in cellars. Gruyère-family but distinct. France's most consumed AOC cheese."
def "cheese:beaufort" "AOC hard cow's milk cheese from Savoie Alps. 'Prince of Gruyères.' Rich, fruity, slightly sweet. Characteristic concave rind from beech wood hoops. Chalets d'alpage version is finest."
def "cheese:gruyere_france" "Hard cow's milk cheese produced in France (distinct from Swiss Gruyère AOP). Firm, slightly grainy, nutty, sweet, fruity. Used in French onion soup and croque monsieur. Franche-Comté production."
def "cheese:emmental_france" "Hard cow's milk cheese with characteristic large holes (eyes). Mild, sweet, nutty. French Emmental production in eastern France and Brittany. Distinct from Swiss Emmental AOP."
def "cheese:munster" "AOC washed-rind cow's milk cheese from Alsace-Lorraine. Orange rind from brine washing. Pungent aroma, milder interior flavor. Often served with cumin seeds. Made in round forms."
def "cheese:epoisses" "AOC washed-rind cow's milk cheese from Burgundy. Marc de Bourgogne-washed rind. Intensely pungent (once banned on Paris public transport), creamy interior. Spoon-soft when ripe."
def "cheese:livarot" "AOC washed-rind cow's milk cheese from Normandy. 'Colonel' — orange stripes from sedge grass wrapping. Strong aroma, supple interior, beefy flavor. Norman specialty since Middle Ages."
def "cheese:pont_leveque" "AOC washed-rind cow's milk cheese from Calvados, Normandy. Square shape, orange-brown rind, pungent, mild earthy interior. One of France's oldest cheeses (12th century origin)."
def "cheese:chaource" "AOC soft-ripened cow's milk cheese from Aube, Champagne. Cylindrical, bloomy rind, chalky-to-creamy interior, mild lactic and mushroom flavor. Young (2 weeks) or aged (4-8 weeks)."
def "cheese:reblochon" "AOC soft to semi-soft cow's milk cheese from Haute-Savoie. Washed rind, supple interior, mild, creamy, nutty flavor. Essential ingredient in tartiflette. Farm (fermier) and dairy versions."
def "cheese:morbier" "AOC semi-soft cow's milk cheese from Franche-Comté. Distinctive layer of vegetable ash running through center (originally separated morning and evening milks). Supple, fruity, slightly smoky."
def "cheese:cantal" "AOC hard cow's milk cheese from Auvergne; one of France's oldest cheeses (2000+ years). Firm, slightly crumbly, tangy, buttery. Three ages: Jeune (30-60 days), Entre-deux, Vieux (240+ days)."
def "cheese:salers" "AOC hard cow's milk cheese from Auvergne, made only when cows graze on summer pastures. Rustic, firm, complex, slightly sharp. Made in traditional wooden vats (gerle). Sister to Cantal."
def "cheese:laguiole" "AOC hard cow's milk cheese from Aubrac plateau, Aveyron. Pressed, uncooked, slightly fruity and grassy. Made at high-altitude burons (mountain huts) from June to October. Very rare production."
def "cheese:ossau_iraty" "AOC hard sheep's milk cheese from Basque Country and Béarn, Pyrénées. Firm, smooth paste, nutty, sweet, mild herb notes. One of France's great PDO cheeses; summer pasture milk best."
def "cheese:rocamadour" "AOC fresh to soft goat's milk cheese from Lot, Quercy. Tiny disc, sometimes eaten very young (fresh) or with more bloom rind (affiné). Mild, creamy, slightly tangy. Pilgrim town namesake."
def "cheese:valencay" "AOC soft goat's milk cheese from Berry, Centre-Val de Loire. Distinctive truncated pyramid shape, dusted with vegetable ash. Chalky to creamy interior, tangy, citrus, hazelnut notes."
def "cheese:selles_sur_cher" "AOC soft goat's milk cheese from Loire Valley. Flattened disc dusted with ash and charcoal. Chalky young, creamy when aged. Mild goat flavor, lemony acidity. Classic Loire Valley chèvre."
def "cheese:crottin_de_chavignol" "AOC goat's milk cheese from Sancerre area, Loire Valley. Small, firm drum shape. Young: white, mild, creamy. Aged: brown, hard, pungent, nutty. Classic pairing with Sancerre Sauvignon Blanc."
def "cheese:charolais_cheese" "AOC goat's milk cheese from Charolais area, Burgundy. Cylindrical, natural rind, slightly wrinkled. Eaten young (fresh and mild) or aged (more flavor, firmer). Becoming more widely recognized."
def "cheese:bleu_dauvergne" "AOC blue cow's milk cheese from Auvergne. Foil-wrapped, creamy, moist, sharp and spicy blue. Similar to Roquefort but with cow's milk; more accessible and milder in price. Crumbly paste."
def "cheese:fourme_dambert" "AOC blue cow's milk cheese from Auvergne. Cylindrical, tall, natural rind. Mild, creamy blue; one of France's gentlest blues. Among the oldest French cheeses (7th century records). Supple paste."
def "cheese:bleu_de_bresse" "Semi-soft blue cow's milk cheese from Bresse/Ain, Burgundy. Mild, creamy, foil-wrapped small cylinders. Factory-produced; not PDO. Milder and more accessible than Roquefort or Fourme d'Ambert."

# ── Italy — DOP Cheeses ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:parmigiano_reggiano" "DOP extra-hard cow's milk cheese from Emilia-Romagna. 'King of cheeses.' Minimum 12 months (Stravecchio 30+). Granular, crystalline, complex umami. No additives permitted. Rind is edible."
def "cheese:grana_padano" "DOP extra-hard cow's milk cheese from Po Valley (broader zone than Parmigiano). Similar granular texture; aged 9-24 months. Slightly milder and more affordable than Parmigiano-Reggiano."
def "cheese:pecorino_romano" "DOP hard sheep's milk cheese, originally from Lazio (now also Sardinia and Tuscany). Sharp, salty, tangy. Ancient Roman staple. Used grated in pasta (cacio e pepe, amatriciana, carbonara)."
def "cheese:pecorino_toscano" "DOP sheep's milk cheese from Tuscany. Softer and milder than Pecorino Romano; eaten fresh (fresco) or semi-aged (stagionato). Grassy, buttery, mild. Pairs with honey and figs."
def "cheese:pecorino_sardo" "DOP sheep's milk cheese from Sardinia. Two types: Dolce (semi-soft, mild, young) and Maturo (hard, sharp, aged). Rich sheep's milk flavor with distinct Sardinian herbal/floral character."
def "cheese:gorgonzola" "DOP blue cow's milk cheese from Lombardy and Piedmont. Two styles: Dolce (young, creamy, mild) and Piccante/Naturale (firm, sharp, piquant, aged 6-12 months). Classic Italian blue."
def "cheese:taleggio" "DOP washed-rind cow's milk cheese from Lombardy. Square shape, thin orange rind, soft interior. Meaty, fruity, mild pungency. Excellent melting cheese. One of Italy's oldest cheeses."
def "cheese:fontina_dop" "DOP semi-soft cow's milk cheese from Aosta Valley. Distinctive sweet, nutty, earthy flavor. Holes from gas bubbles. Used in fonduta (Italian fondue). Made from whole milk of Valdostana cows."
def "cheese:asiago" "DOP cow's milk cheese from Veneto and Trentino. Two types: Pressato (fresh, mild, semi-soft) and d'Allevo/Stagionato (aged, harder, sharper). Mountain cheese of ancient tradition."
def "cheese:montasio" "DOP hard cow's milk cheese from Friuli and Veneto. Firm, fruity when young; sharp and complex when aged. Used in frico (Friulian cheese crisp). Mountain pasture origin."
def "cheese:ragusano" "DOP hard cow's milk cheese from Ragusa, Sicily (pasta filata style). Rectangular block, sharp, complex flavor. Made from Modicana cow milk. Aged hanging from ropes. Ancient Sicilian tradition."
def "cheese:mozzarella_di_bufala" "DOP fresh buffalo milk cheese from Campania (and Lazio). Snow-white, high moisture, elastic, milky, slightly sour. Protected since 1993. Eaten fresh within days. Basis of pizza Napoletana DOC."
def "cheese:provolone" "DOP pasta filata cow's milk cheese from southern Italy (now mainly Lombardy). Two types: Dolce (mild, young) and Piccante (sharp, aged). Pear or sausage shapes, often smoked."
def "cheese:scamorza" "Semi-soft pasta filata cow's milk cheese from southern Italy. Pear-shaped, white or smoked (affumicata, golden-brown). Milder than Provolone; excellent grilled or melted. Fresh and smoked versions."
def "cheese:burrata" "Fresh cow's milk cheese from Puglia. Outer shell of mozzarella filled with stracciatella (shredded mozzarella) and cream. Extremely perishable; best within 24 hours. Rich, indulgent, sweet cream."
def "cheese:ricotta" "Fresh whey cheese from cow, sheep, goat, or buffalo milk across Italy. Light, grainy, slightly sweet. Not a true cheese (made from whey, not curd). Used in pasta, desserts, and as a spread."
def "cheese:mascarpone" "Fresh cow's milk cream cheese from Lombardy. Made from cream (not milk) with acid coagulation. Very high fat, thick, sweet, spreadable. Used in tiramisu, risotto, pasta sauces."
def "cheese:strachino" "Fresh to soft cow's milk cheese from Lombardy. Very soft, mild, creamy, slightly acidic. Used spread on bread or as pizza topping. Related to Crescenza; both are Stracchino family."
def "cheese:caciocavallo" "Semi-hard to hard pasta filata cow's milk cheese from southern Italy. Gourd shape tied with rope. Mild when young (dolce), sharp when aged (stagionato/silano). Ancient southern Italian tradition."
def "cheese:bitto" "DOP hard cow's milk cheese (with addition of goat's milk permitted) from Lombardy Valtellina Alps. Made only in summer (June-October). Aged 70 days to 10+ years. Complex, floral, fruity."

# ── Spain — DO/DOP Cheeses ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:manchego" "DOP hard sheep's milk cheese from La Mancha, Castile. Herringbone rind pattern (from esparto grass mold), ivory paste with small holes. Buttery, nutty, mild tangy. Spain's most famous cheese."
def "cheese:cabrales" "DOP blue cheese from Asturias. Made from mixed cow, sheep, and goat milk. Wrapped in maple leaves, cured in limestone mountain caves. Intense, sharp, piquant, creamy. Strong and complex."
def "cheese:idiazabal" "DOP hard sheep's milk cheese from Basque Country and Navarre. Often smoked over cherry or beech wood. Compact, firm, slightly tangy, smoky. Latxa and Carranzana sheep milk."
def "cheese:mahon" "DOP semi-hard to hard cow's milk cheese from Menorca, Balearic Islands. Rubbed with olive oil, paprika, and butter (giving orange exterior). Mild young (tierno), sharp aged (añejo)."
def "cheese:torta_del_casar" "DOP soft sheep's milk cheese from Extremadura. Thistle rennet coagulation (cardoon). Spoonable, intensely creamy interior at room temperature. Pungent, bitter, complex. Eaten by cutting the top."
def "cheese:tetilla" "DOP soft to semi-soft cow's milk cheese from Galicia. Distinctive pear/cone shape (tetilla = 'little breast'). Mild, buttery, creamy, slightly acidic. Pairs with local seafood and Albariño."
def "cheese:zamorano" "DOP hard sheep's milk cheese from Zamora, Castile and León. Firm, compact, herringbone rind. Richer and stronger than Manchego. Churra and Castellana sheep milk. Complex, slightly spicy."
def "cheese:roncal" "DOP hard sheep's milk cheese from Roncal Valley, Navarre. Spain's first designated PDO cheese (1981). Firm, compact, strong, slightly sharp and spicy. Latxa sheep milk. 4-7 months aging."

# ── Switzerland / Germany / Austria / Netherlands ──────────────────────────────

def "cheese:gruyere_aop" "AOP hard cow's milk cheese from Gruyères, Fribourg, Switzerland. No holes (unlike Emmental). Sweet, nutty, fruity, slightly salty. Essential in fondue and raclette. 5-18+ months aging."
def "cheese:emmental_aop" "AOP hard cow's milk cheese from Emmental, Bern, Switzerland. Large characteristic holes (eyes). Sweet, mild, nutty. World's most imitated cheese. Traditional wheels weigh 80-100kg."
def "cheese:appenzeller" "Hard cow's milk cheese from Appenzell, Switzerland. Rubbed with herbal brine (secret recipe). Pungent aroma, complex spicy-herbal flavor, smooth paste. Three aging grades: Classic, Surchoix, Extra."
def "cheese:raclette_du_valais" "AOP semi-hard cow's milk cheese from Valais, Switzerland. Meltable; scraped onto potatoes for raclette dish. Mild, nutty, slightly pungent when heated. Traditional Swiss Alpine cheese."
def "cheese:sbrinz" "AOP extra-hard cow's milk cheese from central Switzerland. One of Europe's oldest cheeses (pre-Roman). Very hard, granular, intense, nutty. Aged minimum 18 months (up to 3+ years). Similar to Parmesan."
def "cheese:tilsiter" "Semi-hard cow's milk cheese from Tilsit (now Sovetsk, Russia, orig. East Prussia). Made in Switzerland and Germany. Mild to pungent, small irregular holes. Often with caraway seeds. Washed rind variants."
def "cheese:vacherin_mont_dor" "AOP soft washed-rind cow's milk cheese from Jura, produced only between August and March. Sold in spruce boxes; baked whole in oven. Intensely creamy and spoonable. Seasonal Swiss specialty."
def "cheese:gouda" "Semi-hard to hard cow's milk cheese from South Holland, Netherlands. Mild young (jonge), complex aged (oud, overjarig with caramel/butterscotch/crystalline). World's most consumed cheese type."
def "cheese:edam" "Semi-hard cow's milk cheese from North Holland. Iconic red wax rind for export (yellow for domestic). Mild, slightly salty, nutty. Low-fat for a cheese. Named for port city of Edam."
def "cheese:leerdammer" "Semi-hard cow's milk cheese from Netherlands. Cherry-sized holes, mild, sweet, slightly nutty flavor. Trademarked; Maasdam is similar generic name. Developed 1977 as Swiss-style Dutch cheese."
def "cheese:limburger" "Washed-rind cow's milk cheese originally from Limburg, Belgium; now mainly produced in Germany and USA. Extremely pungent aroma from Brevibacterium linens; milder taste than smell suggests."
def "cheese:allgauer_emmentaler" "Hard cow's milk cheese from Allgäu, Bavaria. German cousin of Swiss Emmental with large holes. PDO protected. Mild, sweet, nutty. Major German cheese-producing region in Alpine foothills."
def "cheese:bergkase" "Generic term for Alpine hard cow's milk cheese ('mountain cheese') from Austria and Bavaria. Made at high altitude in summer from pasture milk. Rich, complex, nutty. Austrian Vorarlberger Bergkäse is PDO."

# ── UK / Ireland ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:cheddar" "Hard pressed cow's milk cheese from Somerset, England. Cheddaring process (stacking curds). Ranges from mild (2 months) to extra mature (24+ months). Crumbly, tangy, sharp. World's most copied style."
def "cheese:stilton" "PDO blue cow's milk cheese from Nottinghamshire, Derbyshire, Leicestershire. 'King of English cheeses.' Cylindrical, natural rind, rich and complex blue veining. Blue (classic) and White varieties."
def "cheese:red_leicester" "Hard pressed cow's milk cheese from Leicestershire. Distinctive orange color from annatto. Mild, slightly nutty, rich. Flaky texture. One of England's oldest traditional cheeses."
def "cheese:double_gloucester" "Hard pressed cow's milk cheese from Gloucestershire. Orange color from annatto, smooth and rich. Milder than Cheddar, buttery. Used in traditional Gloucester cheese rolling competition."
def "cheese:wensleydale" "Hard to crumbly cow's milk cheese (sometimes mixed with sheep) from North Yorkshire. White, crumbly, mild, slightly sweet and honeyed. Celebrated by Aardman's Wallace & Gromit as favorite."
def "cheese:lancashire_cheese" "Crumbly to creamy cow's milk cheese from Lancashire. Three styles: Crumbly (young, fresh, lemony), Creamy (medium), Tasty (mature, complex). Excellent toasting cheese. Traditional northern English."
def "cheese:cheshire_cheese" "Crumbly pressed cow's milk cheese from Cheshire (one of England's oldest). White, Red (annatto), and Blue varieties. Mild, salty, slightly acidic, crumbly. Mentioned in Domesday Book (1086)."
def "cheese:caerphilly" "Semi-soft pressed cow's milk cheese from Wales. Mild, slightly salty, lemony, moist and crumbly. Originally made to feed Welsh miners. Revived by Somerset artisan dairies; Welsh production returning."
def "cheese:celtic_promise" "Washed-rind cow's milk cheese from Wales, washed with Calvados. Soft, supple, pungent aroma, mild creamy interior. Created by John Savage-Onslow. Award-winning modern Welsh artisan cheese."
def "cheese:cornish_yarg" "Semi-hard cow's milk cheese from Cornwall, England. Distinctive coating of nettles (stinging nettles pressed onto rind). Mild, lemon, slight mushroom from rind. Crumbly center, creamy under rind."

# ── Greece / Cyprus ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:feta" "PDO soft brined sheep's milk cheese (up to 30% goat's milk) from mainland Greece and Lesbos. White, crumbly, tangy, salty. Stored in brine. UNESCO intangible heritage. Essential in Greek cuisine."
def "cheese:graviera" "PDO hard cow's or sheep's milk cheese from Crete (Graviera Kritis) and Naxos (Graviera Naxou). Greece's second most popular cheese. Nutty, sweet, mild. Similar to Gruyère; cooked pressed wheels."
def "cheese:kefalotiri" "Hard sheep's and goat's milk cheese from Greece and Cyprus. Sharp, salty, firm. Used grated on pasta or fried as saganaki. One of Greece's oldest cheeses. Related to Kefalotyri variants."
def "cheese:kasseri" "PDO semi-hard sheep's milk cheese (up to 20% goat) from Macedonia and Thessaly. Elastic, mild, buttery, slightly salty. Pasta filata style. Popular for saganaki (pan-fried). Greek table cheese."
def "cheese:manouri" "PDO fresh Greek whey cheese (with added cream). Creamy, soft, white, mild, slightly sweet. From Macedonia and Thessaly. Made from whey of Feta or Kefalotyri. Dessert and pastry use."
def "cheese:halloumi" "PDO semi-hard brined sheep and goat milk cheese from Cyprus (now with cow's milk allowed). Does not melt when grilled or fried. Squeaky, salty, mild. Summer grass mint often pressed in. Iconic."

# ── Scandinavia ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:jarlsberg" "Semi-hard cow's milk cheese from Norway. Large holes, mild sweet nutty flavor similar to Swiss Emmental. Created 1956 at Agricultural University of Norway. Major export cheese worldwide."
def "cheese:havarti" "Semi-soft cow's milk cheese from Denmark. Smooth, supple, mild, buttery, slightly acidic. Named after Havartigaard farm (Hanne Nielsen, 1850s). Many flavored varieties (caraway, dill, cream)."
def "cheese:danbo" "Semi-hard cow's milk cheese from Denmark. Mild, slightly sweet, rubbery. Often with caraway seeds. Denmark's most consumed domestic cheese. Also called Samsoe (from Samsø island variant)."
def "cheese:gjetost" "Norwegian brown goat and/or cow whey cheese (Brunost). Made by boiling whey until caramelization. Very sweet, fudge-like, caramel flavor. Eaten thinly sliced on bread. National Norwegian cheese."

# ── Eastern Europe ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:bryndza" "PDO soft sheep's milk cheese from Slovakia (Bryndza Slovenská) and Romania. Creamy, crumbly, tangy, salty. Made from Valaška sheep. Used in traditional halusky (potato dumplings). Protected 2008."
def "cheese:oscypek_poland" "PDO smoked sheep's milk cheese from Tatra Mountains, Poland. Traditional spindle or barrel shape, carved patterns. Firm, slightly salty, smoky. Made by shepherds (baca) on highland pastures."
def "cheese:kashkaval" "Hard sheep's or cow's milk pasta filata cheese from Balkans (Bulgaria, Romania, Macedonia). Yellow, firm, slightly sharp and salty. Similar to Caciocavallo. Eastern European table and cooking cheese."

# ── Americas ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:monterey_jack" "Semi-soft cow's milk cheese from Monterey, California. Mild, buttery, creamy. Melts well. Created by Franciscan monks, commercialized by David Jacks in 1890s. Widely used in American cuisine."
def "cheese:colby" "Semi-hard cow's milk cheese from Colby, Wisconsin. Similar to Cheddar but washed-curd process keeps it moister and milder. Orange color from annatto. American original variety (1885)."
def "cheese:pepper_jack" "Semi-soft cow's milk cheese, a Monterey Jack variant with sweet peppers, jalapeños, and spices mixed in. Mild heat, creamy texture. Popular in American Tex-Mex cuisine and burgers."
def "cheese:queso_fresco" "Fresh cow's milk (or mixed) cheese used across Latin America and Mexico. White, crumbly, mild, slightly salty. Does not melt. Crumbled over tacos, enchiladas, beans. Similar to Indian paneer."
def "cheese:queso_oaxaca" "Semi-soft pasta filata cow's milk cheese from Oaxaca, Mexico. String cheese wound into balls. Mild, creamy, excellent meltability. Used in quesadillas, tlayudas. Mexican mozzarella analog."
def "cheese:queso_blanco" "Fresh cow's milk (sometimes goat) cheese used in Latin America. White, firm yet crumbly, mild, slightly tangy. Higher melting point; holds shape when fried or heated. Versatile Latin kitchen cheese."

# ── Middle East / South Asia ──────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:labneh" "Fresh strained yogurt cheese from Levant (Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Palestine). Thick, creamy, tangy, spreadable. Served with olive oil and za'atar. Aged versions (rolled in herbs, oil-preserved)."
def "cheese:shanklish" "Aged cow's or sheep's milk cheese from Syria and Lebanon. Shaped into balls, rolled in dried thyme and chili flakes. Sharp, pungent, crumbly. Often served with tomatoes and onions."
def "cheese:paneer" "Fresh non-melting cow's or buffalo milk cheese from Indian subcontinent. White, firm, mild, slightly sweet. Made by acid coagulation. Used in palak paneer, paneer tikka, curries. No rennet used."
def "cheese:surati_paneer" "Fresh soft buffalo milk cheese from Surat, Gujarat, India. Stored in whey. Softer and more delicate than standard paneer. Regional specialty; milder flavor with slightly sour whey notes."
def "cheese:chhena" "Fresh cow's or buffalo milk cheese from eastern India (Bengal, Odisha). Very soft, crumbly, moist. Base for Bengali sweets: rasgulla, sandesh, rasmalai. Similar to ricotta but less sweet."

